}
draw((2,2)--(4,2),linewidth(1));
label("A",(2,2),SW);
label("B",(4,2),SE);
draw((0,1)--(6,1),dashed);
draw((0,3)--(6,3),dashed);
draw((0,4)--(6,4),dashed);
draw((0,5)--(6,5),dashed);
[/asy]

If $C$ is on one of the horizontal lines passing through the $4$ points to the left of $AB,$ then $ABC$ will be isosceles if $C$ is one of the $2$ points on the line closest to $AB,$ for a total of $2$ points.  Similarly, if $C$ is on one of the horizontal lines passing through the $4$ points to the right of $AB,$ then $ABC$ will be isosceles if $C$ is one of the $2$ points on the line closest to $AB,$ for a total of $2$ points.  Thus, there are a total of $2+2=\boxed{4}$ points that will result in triangle $ABC$ being isosceles.

